## 3. Other Psychological and Social Barriers

### 3.1 Lack of Insight and Mental Health Literacy

A significant barrier is **lack of insight** or denial of illness, especially in severe mental illnesses like schizophrenia, where anosognosia affects up to 50% of patients ([Susman, 2019](https://www.advocatingforbettermentalhealth.com/8-reasons-why-people-dont-get-treatment-for-mental-illness/)). Additionally, limited **mental health literacy**—knowledge and beliefs about mental disorders—impedes recognition of symptoms and understanding of treatment benefits ([Henderson et al., 2013](https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/full/10.2105/AJPH.2012.300796)).

### 3.2 Feelings of Inadequacy and Hopelessness

Many individuals feel they should manage problems independently and view help-seeking as a sign of weakness or failure ([Susman, 2019](https://www.advocatingforbettermentalhealth.com/8-reasons-why-people-dont-get-treatment-for-mental-illness/)). Depression and hopelessness further reduce motivation to seek care.

### 3.3 Distrust of Providers and Confidentiality Concerns

Distrust of healthcare providers and fear that personal information will not remain confidential are significant deterrents ([Tap into Safety, 2017](https://tapintosafety.com/stigma-and-barriers-to-mental-health-care/)). Negative past experiences with providers exacerbate these concerns.

---

## 4. Structural and Practical Barriers

### 4.1 Access and Availability

Limited availability of mental health services, especially in rural or underserved areas, restricts access ([Susman, 2019](https://www.advocatingforbettermentalhealth.com/8-reasons-why-people-dont-get-treatment-for-mental-illness/)). Lack of transportation, inconvenient clinic hours, and long wait times further hinder help-seeking ([Taber, Leyva, & Persoskie, 2015](https://doi.org/10.1007/s11606-014-3089-1)).

### 4.2 Financial Barriers

Cost concerns, including lack of insurance or high co-pays, are primary reasons for avoidance ([Taber et al., 2015](https://doi.org/10.1007/s11606-014-3089-1)). Although insurance coverage has improved in some countries, financial hardship remains a critical obstacle.

### 4.3 Scheduling and Work Constraints

Difficulty scheduling appointments and conflicts with work or school schedules deter many from seeking care ([Tap into Safety, 2017](https://tapintosafety.com/stigma-and-barriers-to-mental-health-care/)).

---

## 5. Emotional and Cognitive Barriers

### 5.1 Fear and Embarrassment

Fear of diagnosis, treatment procedures, or stigma-related judgment causes avoidance. Embarrassment about symptoms or mental health status is common ([Taber et al., 2015](https://doi.org/10.1007/s11606-014-3089-1)).

### 5.2 Negative Expectations of Treatment

Some individuals expect treatment to be ineffective or fear side effects of medications, leading to reluctance ([Susman, 2019](https://www.advocatingforbettermentalhealth.com/8-reasons-why-people-dont-get-treatment-for-mental-illness/)).

---

## 6. Conceptual Model of Help-Seeking Avoidance

Based on qualitative data, medical care avoidance—including mental health care—can be conceptualized through three main categories ([Taber et al., 2015](https://doi.org/10.1007/s11606-014-3089-1)):

| Category                        | Description                                                                                   | Examples                                   |
|--------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------|
| Low Perceived Need              | Belief that care is unnecessary or symptoms will resolve spontaneously                         | "Not sick enough," "Will get better alone" |
| Traditional Barriers            | External obstacles limiting access or ability to seek care                                   | Cost, transportation, scheduling conflicts |
| Unfavorable Evaluations         | Negative perceptions or experiences related to care or providers                             | Distrust, fear, embarrassment               |

This model aligns with Crisis Decision Theory, suggesting that individuals appraise threat, evaluate available options, and weigh desirability before seeking care.

