## 7. Impact of Public Health Programs and Interventions

National anti-stigma campaigns (e.g., England's *Time to Change*) aim to improve mental health literacy and reduce stigma ([Henderson et al., 2013](https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/full/10.2105/AJPH.2012.300796)). While these programs have shown promise in improving attitudes and knowledge, evidence for increased help-seeking remains inconclusive due to methodological limitations and lack of control groups.

Key findings from evaluations include:

- Mental health knowledge predicts intentions to seek help and disclose illness.
- Positive attitudes toward community care support help-seeking more than the mere absence of negative attitudes.
- Campaign awareness alone does not guarantee increased help-seeking intentions.

Interventions targeting disclosure concerns, internalized stigma, and treatment stigma may be particularly effective. Multi-faceted approaches addressing stigma alongside practical barriers are recommended.

---

## 8. Summary of Key Barriers to Mental Health Help-Seeking

| Barrier Type             | Description                                                                                   | Prevalence / Impact                             |
|-------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| **Stigma**              | Public, self, anticipated, and treatment stigma; disclosure concerns                          | Moderate barrier; 21-32% report stigma-related barriers ([Clement et al., 2015](https://doi.org/10.1017/S0033291714000129)) |
| **Lack of Insight**     | Denial or unawareness of illness, anosognosia                                                | Significant in severe mental illness            |
| **Mental Health Literacy** | Limited knowledge of symptoms and treatment benefits                                         | Impedes recognition and help-seeking            |
| **Distrust and Confidentiality** | Fear of judgment, mistrust of providers, confidentiality concerns                        | Common deterrent                                 |
| **Practical Barriers**  | Cost, insurance, transportation, scheduling, availability                                    | Most common barriers; cost cited by 24% ([Taber et al., 2015](https://doi.org/10.1007/s11606-014-3089-1)) |
| **Emotional Barriers**  | Fear of diagnosis, embarrassment, hopelessness                                              | Frequently reported                              |
| **Cultural and Social Factors** | Minority status, gender norms, occupational culture                                       | Disproportionate impact on specific groups      |

